  1. The data from contains the velocities of 82 galaxies from six well-separated conic sections of space (Postman et al., 1986, Roeder, 1990). The data are intended to shed light on whether or not the observable universe contains superclusters of galaxies surrounded by large voids. The evidence for the existence of superclusters would be the multimodality of the distribution of velocities.(8.1 Handbook)

    a.) Construct histograms using the following functions:

    -hist() and ggplot()+geom_histogram()

-truehist() and ggplot+geom_histogram() (pay attention to the y-axis!)

-qplot()

Comment on the shape and distribution of the variable based on the three plots. (Hint: Also play around with binning)

My Thoughts: Both histograms and “truehist” histograms had similar shapes. The histograms for the part a) used count in the y-axis while the histograms for part b) used frequency. It looks like the frequency in part b) does not add to 1, however.Lastly, qplot (also using frequency on y-axis) looks different from the rest of the histograms as there are gaps between velocity data.

b.) Create a new variable \textit{loggalaxies} = $\log$(galaxies). Construct histograms using the functions in part a.) and comment on the shape and differences.

My Thoughts: The histogram looks similar to truehist again (now using log velocity). We see a frequency in truehist that doesn’t look like it will add up to 1, which is confusing. Looking online some people suggested it may be a probability density issue if the variance is less than 1. And we also see qplot has narrower bins than the other two histograms. Qplot, also with frequency as the y-axis, again shows separation between velocities.

My Thoughts: The histograms from the first part of the question make me think there is either 2 or 3 superclusters, one in the middle and two on the edge. My Thoughts: The data was structured as birth rate vs death rate with density as the y axis. 4 clusters were found by the EM algorithm with means around birth rate of 55.94967 43.80396 19.922913 33.730672 and means around death rate of 29.34960 12.09411 9.081348 8.535812 (the four numbers for birth and death make a coordinate with each other for each of the four numbers in the sequnce). What this data shows is basically the replacement rate (without accounting for immigration/emmigration),when birth is higher than death you grow and vice versa.This clustering shows countries that may be shrinking some that are stagnant and some that may be growing, but it allows us to gain o what countries will be a population growth center.

  1. A sex difference in the age of onset of schizophrenia was noted by Kraepelin (1919). Subsequent epidemiological studies of the disorder have consistently shown an earlier onset in men than in women. One model that has been suggested to explain this observed difference is known as the subtype model which postulates two types of schizophrenia, one characterized by early onset, typical symptoms and poor premorbid competence; and the other by late onset, atypical symptoms and good premorbid competence. The early onset type is assumed to be largely a disorder of men and the late onset largely a disorder of women. Fit finite mixutres of normal densities separately to the onset data for men and women given in the data from . See if you can produce some evidence for or against the subtype model. (8.3 Handbook)

My Thoughts: Based on the data available (~150 males and ~100 females) it appears males are diagnosed at younger ages, peaking around 20 while females are at the peak for being diagnosed later between 25 and 30.

My Thoughts: We see that the distribution of diagnosis with schizophrenia is more unimodal in men and bimodal in women. Both men and women are highly diagnosed in their early to mid twenties but there is a second age of high diagnosis for women in their late 40s. I would say this means both men and women are at risk in their early twenties and women are at higher risk again in late 40s but this may be due to low sample size. A larger sample size may create a more unimodal distribution for women.
